    "We introduce the linear filter k, (for the moment an unknown time series), that can be applied to a vector a through the standard scalar productâ ≡ i a i k i ≡ a T k.(22)To find the filter k that maximises the SNR ( 21), we rewrite the latter in terms of the filtered functions ĥ and nSNR = P ĥ P n = E[(h T k) T (h T k)] E[(n T k) T (n T k)] = E[ k T h 2] E[k T nn T k] = k T h 2 k T E[n T n]k = k T h 2 k T C nn k, (23)where we have used that also the filter k is deterministic.",
    "Define the scalar product between two vectors a and b, weighted with the inverse autocovariance matrixa|b ≡ a T C -1 nn b.",
    "(24)Then, Eq.",
    "( 23) can be written in terms of the scalar product (24) asSNR = C nn k|h 2 C nn k|C nn k = (C nn k) T C -1 nn h 2 (C nn k) T C -1 nn C nn k = k T h 2 k T C nn k. (25)Equation (25) conveys that the filtered SNR is proportional to the square of the scalar product C nn k|h, therefore it is maximum when this scalar product is maximum.",
    "Geometrically, this happens when the vector C nn k is parallel to h. Therefore, the filter k * that maximises the SNR isC nn k * h ⇒ k * ≡ α C -1 nn h,(26)for some constant α. k * is known as the matched filter."
